name: app.R
content:
library(shiny) library(shinylive) library(usethis) library(shinydashboard) library(bslib) library(DT) library(palmerpenguins) library(dplyr) library(htmltools) library(httpuv) mode_effects <- readRDS("mode_effects.RDS") studies_info <- readRDS("studies_info.RDS") ui <- navbarPage(title="MODE EFFECTS", tabPanel(title="Introduction", uiOutput("introduction")), tabPanel(title="Mode effects", dataTableOutput("table_mode_effects")), tabPanel(title="Details of each study", dataTableOutput("table_studies")), navbarMenu(title="About", tabPanel("Project", uiOutput("project")), tabPanel("Authors", page_navbar( accordion( accordion_panel( "Georgia Tomova", uiOutput("georgia_info") ), accordion_panel( "Richard Silverwood", uiOutput("richard_info") ), accordion_panel( "Liam Wright", uiOutput("liam_info") )))), tabPanel("Further resources", uiOutput("resources") ))) server <- function(input, output) { output$table_mode_effects <- renderDataTable({ table_mode_effects <- datatable(mode_effects, rownames=FALSE, extensions=c("SearchBuilder", "DateTime"), options = list( dom = "Qlfrtip", searchBuilder = TRUE, dom = 't', lengthMenu = list(c(50, 100, 200, -1), c('50', '100', '200', 'All')), pageLength = 100 ), filter = "top", escape = FALSE) table_mode_effects}) output$table_studies <- renderDataTable({ table_studies <- datatable(studies_info, rownames=FALSE, extensions=c("SearchBuilder", "DateTime"), options = list( dom = "Qlfrtip", searchBuilder = TRUE, dom = 't', lengthMenu = list(c(10, 50, -1), c('10', '50', 'All')), pageLength = 50 ), filter = "top", escape = FALSE) table_studies}) output$introduction <- renderUI({HTML("Welcome to the database of survey mode effects!
This searchable and interactive database contains a comprehensive record of mode effects reported in the literature. Here you will find mode effect estimates obtained from experimental or quasi-experimental studies that have been conducted either as part of established existing surveys, in the general population, or age-, sex-, or region-specific strata of the general population.

The mode effects have been located using a systematic search of the bibliographic databases Scopus, Embase 1974-2025, MEDLINE 1946-2025, Health and Psychosocial Instruments, APA PsycInfo, APA PsycExtra, Web of Science Core Collection, as well as Google Scholar, and a search within the citations and references of relevant studies.

Note: This is a work-in-progress project and the database will be updated to include a more complete record of estimated mode effects.

How to use:
1.To use the database, navigate to the 'Mode effects' tab, where you can search for mode effect estimates based on item category, survey population, year of publication, country, and other details. All fields are searchable or have an available drop-down menu to make it easier to find relevant mode effect estimates.
2. To see more details about the study from which a mode effect estimate is obtained, you can search the tab 'Details of each study' using the provided digital object identifier (DOI) of the paper (or, rarely, another identifier if a DOI is not available).

Things to note:
• Not all relevant values were reported in all studies. Where possible, we have derived additional measures based on the information provided. Any values that have been derived post-hoc are formatted in italics.
• Where a cell is empty, this means that no sufficient information was reported in the study to allow for direct extraction or derivation. ")}) output$project <- renderUI({HTML("This database is part of the 'Assessing and Disseminating Methods for Handling Mode Effects' project within the larger Survey Futures collaboration, funded by the Economic and Social Research Council (ES/X014150/1).

The study has been pre-registered on the Open Science Framework: https://osf.io/bs5dw")}) output$resources <- renderUI({HTML( 'For a detailed introduction and discussion of methods for handling mode effects, please see the following user guidance:

Wright et al. 2024. Handling Mode Effects in the CLS Cohort Studies')}) output$georgia_info <- renderUI({HTML("Research Fellow, Centre for Longitudinal Studies, UCL.
g.tomova@ucl.ac.uk")}) output$richard_info <- renderUI({HTML("Associate Professor, Centre for Longitudinal Studies, UCL
r.silverwood@ucl.ac.uk" )}) output$liam_info <- renderUI({HTML("Lecturer, Centre for Longitudinal Studies, UCL
liam.wright@ucl.ac.uk" )}) } shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

name: prep.R
content:
library(dplyr)

# load data
mode_effects <- readxl::read_excel("/Users/qtnzgdt/Library/CloudStorage/OneDrive-UniversityCollegeLondon/Research/Systematic Review/R Shiny/mode_effects/studies_mode_effects_250701.xlsx", skip=1,col_names = TRUE)
studies_info <- readxl::read_excel("/Users/qtnzgdt/Library/CloudStorage/OneDrive-UniversityCollegeLondon/Research/Systematic Review/R Shiny/mode_effects/studies_info_250701.xlsx", skip=1,col_names = TRUE)

# apply rounding to all unrounded numerical cells
mode_effects <- mode_effects %>% 
  mutate(across(c(14:15,18:33), ~ ifelse(is.na(as.numeric(.x)), .x, sprintf("%.2f", as.numeric(.x)))))

# tweak issues (to be applied to main spreadsheet)
mode_effects[which(mode_effects$`Variable type`=="count"),"Variable type"] <- "Count"
mode_effects[which(mode_effects$`Source population category`=="General population (adolescent)"),"Source population category"] <- "General population (adolescents)"
mode_effects[which(mode_effects$`Survey name`=="European Social Survey"),"Survey name"] <- "European Social Survey (ESS)"

# fill general info in each row
fill_until_text <- function(x) {
  result <- x
  for (i in 2:length(x)) {
    if (is.na(x[i])) {
      result[i] <- result[i-1]
    }
  }
  return(result)
}

mode_effects <- mode_effects %>%
  mutate(
    `Year of publication` = fill_until_text(`Year of publication`),
    DOI = fill_until_text(DOI),
    `Source population category` = fill_until_text(`Source population category`),
    `Survey name` = fill_until_text(`Survey name`),
    `Survey population profile` = fill_until_text(`Survey population profile`),
    `Survey sweep` = fill_until_text(`Survey sweep`),
    Country = fill_until_text(Country)
  )


# turn relevant variables to factors to allow dropdown search menu
mode_effects$`Survey name` <- factor(mode_effects$`Survey name`)
mode_effects$`Source population category` <- factor(mode_effects$`Source population category`)
mode_effects$Country <- factor(mode_effects$Country)
mode_effects$Category <- factor(mode_effects$Category)
mode_effects$`Sub-category` <- factor(mode_effects$`Sub-category`)
mode_effects$`Variable type` <- factor(mode_effects$`Variable type`)
mode_effects$`Mode effect estimand` <- factor(mode_effects$`Mode effect estimand`)
mode_effects$`Effect measure` <- factor(mode_effects$`Effect measure`)

# keep only substantial rows for studies
studies_info <- studies_info %>% filter(!is.na(`Quality of reporting`))

# save into environment
saveRDS(mode_effects, file = "mode_effects.RDS") 
saveRDS(studies_info, file = "studies_info.RDS")
